Central Bank Digital Currencies (CBDCs)
 
A Central Bank Digital Currency (CBDC) is a digital form of a country’s cash, issued and backed by the central bank. 
It has the same value as physical money and is different from private cryptocurrencies like Bitcoin.

Key Features
Issued by the central bank
Stable and safe
Legal tender
Digital version of national currency
Centralized and regulated

Types of CBDCs
Wholesale CBDC: Used by banks for interbank payments
Retail CBDC: Used by the public for daily transactions

How CBDCs Work (Example: India’s e₹)
Stored in digital wallets
Used for person-to-person (P2P) and merchant payments (P2M)
Distributed through banks
Non-interest bearing and convertible to cash
 CBDCs may be implemented using token-based systems (similar to cash) or account-based systems, depending on design choices.

Why CBDCs Are Needed
Support digital payments
Reduce cash usage
Improve financial inclusion
Make transactions faster and cheaper

CBDCs vs Cryptocurrencies
CBDCs
Cryptocurrencies
Issued by central bank
No central authority
Stable value
Price changes often
Regulated
Mostly unregulated
Legal tender
Not legal tender


Global Status
Countries representing over 90% of global GDP are exploring or developing CBDCS
Used in countries like Bahamas, Jamaica, Nigeria
Countries like India are testing retail CBDCs



Conclusion
CBDCs are a safe and modern form of digital money that help improve payment systems while keeping the trust of central banks
 
 
 
 

